rounds.response:
With blinds at 10/20 and 10 chips already posted as the big blind (990 stack vs the SB’s 980), I’m looking down at 3♥ 3♦—a small pocket pair that flops a set roughly 1 time in 8 and is ahead of most non-pair hands pre-flop.  

The single opponent has bet the minimum 20, so the pot is 30 chips and it costs 10 more to call.

Mathematics:
- Effective pot odds: I’m risking 10 to win 30 → 25 % break-even equity.
- Your hand equity vs a random heads-up range (any two cards) is ~55 %, and vs even a fairly wide heads-up steal range (say top-35 %) it’s still ~51–53 %.
- No redraw odds problem; future betting will be in position since I’m on the button.

Calling keeps the pot small and preserves potential implied-odds if I flop a set, which will occur ~11.8 % of the time. Folding is too conservative given the price, and raising small merely builds a bigger pot while bloating a stack that is only 20 chips larger than the SB—there’s no fold equity or other strategic benefit worth that risk.

Therefore, the optimal action is simply to call the extra 10 chips.

[Call]
